      <h2 class="section-title">Understanding Volume Calculations</h2>
      <div class="edu-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>What is Volume?</h3>
          <p>Volume is the measure of three-dimensional space that an object or substance occupies. It is an essential concept in physics, engineering, construction, and daily life. Whether you are filling a swimming pool, calculating shipping costs for a box, or pouring a concrete slab, understanding volume is crucial.</p>
          <p>Unlike area, which measures the 2D surface, volume considers three dimensions: length, width, and height. Standard units include cubic meters, cubic feet, liters, and gallons.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Common Volume Formulas</h3>
          <ul class="steps-list">
            <li><strong>Cube:</strong> V = a³ (side cubed)</li>
            <li><strong>Rectangular Box:</strong> V = l × w × h</li>
            <li><strong>Cylinder:</strong> V = π × r² × h</li>
            <li><strong>Sphere:</strong> V = 4/3 × π × r³</li>
            <li><strong>Cone:</strong> V = 1/3 × π × r² × h</li>
            <li><strong>Pyramid:</strong> V = 1/3 × l × w × h</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Volume vs. Capacity</h3>
          <p>While often used interchangeably, volume and capacity are distinct concepts. Volume describes the amount of space an object takes up, measured in cubic units (e.g., cubic inches). Capacity describes the amount of substance (usually liquid or gas) a container can hold, measured in units like gallons, quarts, or liters.</p>
          <p>Our calculator automatically converts your cubic volume into common capacity units to make practical applications easier.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Unit Conversions Explained</h3>
          <p>Converting between different volume units requires specific multipliers. For example, 1 cubic foot equals exactly 1728 cubic inches (12 × 12 × 12). When converting to liquid volume, 1 cubic foot holds approximately 7.48052 US fluid gallons or 28.3168 liters. A cubic meter represents exactly 1000 liters.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

